  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "Hydraulic brakes operate using a closed system filled with brake fluid to transfer force from the driver to the braking components. When the driver presses the brake pedal, a piston in the master cylinder pushes brake fluid through brake lines toward the wheels. This fluid pressure activates pistons in the brake calipers (for disc brakes) or wheel cylinders (for drum brakes), which then press brake pads or shoes against the rotors or drums. The resulting friction slows down and stops the vehicle. Because the fluid is incompressible, even a small force applied at the pedal is effectively amplified at the wheels, providing reliable and consistent braking performance.",
